The NBA trade deadline featured a ton of deals, including a handful of big names. Let's look at the five biggest transactions starting with ... 
MAGIC GET: PG Markelle Fultz.
76ERS GET: SG/SF Jonathon Simmons, OKC's 2020 1st-rounder (protected 1-20), 2019 2nd-rounder (most favorable of CLE, ORL, POR, HOU).

BUCKS GET: PF Nikola Mirotic.
PELICANS GET: PF/C Jason Smith, SF Stanley Johnson, four second-rounders (DEN's 2019, MIL's 2020, WASH's 2020-21).
PISTONS GET: C Thon Maker.
Credit/Source: Derick E. Hingle, USA TODAY Sports

Caption:
RAPTORS GET: C Marc Gasol.
GRIZZLIES GET: C Jonas Valanciunas, SF CJ Miles, PG Delon Wright, 2024 second-rounder.

MAVERICKS GET: PF Kristaps Porzingis, SG Tim Hardaway Jr., PG Trey Burke, SG Courtney Lee.
KNICKS GET: PG Dennis Smith Jr., C DeAndre Jordan, SG Wesley Matthews, two first-rounders (2021, 2023).

76ERS GET: PF Tobias Harris, PF Mike Scott, C Boban Marjanovic.
CLIPPERS GET: SG Landry Shamet, F Wilson Chandler, PF/C Mike Muscala, two first-rounders (PHI's 2020 protected 1-14, MIA's 2021 unprotected), two second-rounders (DET's in 2021, 2023).

Date: Published 5:01 p.m. ET Feb. 9, 2019 | Updated 6:48 p.m. ET Feb. 9, 2019	Updated 6:48 p.m. ET Feb. 9, 2019
Caption: Miami Heat guard Wayne Ellington. (Photo: Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports)
The Detroit Pistons have signed Wayne Ellington. Let's meet the 31-year-old shooting guard ...
The Minnesota Timberwolves selected Ellington (right) with the 28th overall pick in the 2009 NBA draft out of North Carolina. He is 6 feet 5 and 200 pounds.
Credit/Source: Andre J. Jackson, Detroit Free Press

Caption: He played three seasons at UNC, winning a national championship in 2009 over Michigan State, 89-72, in Detroit. He scored 19 points in the final, including this first-half dunk, and was named the tournament's most outstanding player.
Credit/Source: Julian H. Gonzalez, Detroit Free Press

Caption: Now in his 10th NBA season, Ellington is a career 38 percent 3-point shooter who has averaged eight points, 2.2 rebounds and 1.1 assists over 617 games (139 starts).
This season, Ellington averaged 8.4 points with 36.8 percent 3-point shooting in 25 games with Miami.
Ellington is averaging at least six 3-point attempts per game for the third straight season. His weakness is defense.

Ellington is well traveled, having played for Minnesota, Memphis, Cleveland, Dallas, L.A. Lakers, Brooklyn and Miami, before the trade to Phoenix on Feb. 6. He has played in seven career playoff games (2014 with Dallas, 2018 with Miami).
A native of Wynnewood, Pennsylvania, Ellington attended The Episcopal Academy in Newtown Square, Penn.
Wayne Ellington shoots against Pistons guard Ish Smith on Jan. 28, 2017 in Miami.

Caption: Rep. John Dingell, D-Dearborn, is celebrated by colleagues on Capitol Hill in Washington, D.C., on June 7, 2013, as he becomes the longest-serving member of Congress with his 20,997th day as a representative.

House Minority Leader Nancy Pelosi of Calif. helps former Michigan Rep. John Dingell stand as she passes him the gavel Dingell used 50 years ago when Medicare legislation was passed during an event marking the 50th Anniversary of Medicare and Medicaid, Wednesday, July 29, 2015, on Capitol Hill in Washington.

Retiring Congressman John Dingell getting a hug from his wife Debbie Dingell, right, while greeting Michigan Senator Debbie Stabenow, left, at a reception on Capitol Hill honoring Dingell and Reps. Dave Camp,  Mike Rogers and Sen. Carl Levin who are all departing Congress. Together they have 133 years of service at the Capitol.

In this March 23, 2010, file photo, Marcelas Owens of Seattle, left, Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., right, and others, watch as President Barack Obama signs the health care bill in the East Room of the White House in Washington.
Credit/Source: J. Scott Applewhite, AP, J. Scott Applewhite, AP

Caption: U.S. Rep. John Dingell (D-MI) participates in a news conference and rally to mark the 46th anniversary of the passage of Medicare in the U.S. Capitol Visitors Center July 27, 2011, in Washington, DC.
President Barack Obama presented John Dingell with the Presidential Medal of Freedom. Thousands of Dingell’s papers have been donated to U-M’s Bentley Library.
John Dingell
This undated photo provided by Rep. John Dingell's office, shows the congressman with President John F. Kennedy.
Rep. John Dingell (D-MI) waits to be interviewed on Capitol Hill on Nov. 7, 2009, in Washington, DC.

Rep. John Dingell, D-Mich., left, speaks with England's Prince Harry, and British Ambassador Sir Peter Westmacott, before a reception and dinner at the British Ambassador's residence, Thursday, May 9, 2013, in Washington.

MAGIC GET: PG Markelle Fultz.
76ERS GET: SG/SF Jonathon Simmons, OKC's 2020 1st-rounder (protected 1-20), 2019 2nd-rounder (most favorable of CLE, ORL, POR, HOU).

BUCKS GET: PF Nikola Mirotic.
PELICANS GET: PF/C Jason Smith, SF Stanley Johnson, four second-rounders (DEN's 2019, MIL's 2020, WASH's 2020-21).
PISTONS GET: C Thon Maker.

Caption:
RAPTORS GET: C Marc Gasol.
GRIZZLIES GET: C Jonas Valanciunas, SF CJ Miles, PG Delon Wright, 2024 second-rounder.

MAVERICKS GET: PF Kristaps Porzingis, SG Tim Hardaway Jr., PG Trey Burke, SG Courtney Lee.
KNICKS GET: PG Dennis Smith Jr., C DeAndre Jordan, SG Wesley Matthews, two first-rounders (2021, 2023).

76ERS GET: PF Tobias Harris, PF Mike Scott, C Boban Marjanovic.
CLIPPERS GET: SG Landry Shamet, F Wilson Chandler, PF/C Mike Muscala, two first-rounders (PHI's 2020 protected 1-14, MIA's 2021 unprotected), two second-rounders (DET's in 2021, 2023).

Caption: NA

OLB Josh Allen, Kentucky: Allen seems like a good bet to go in the top five after a 17-sack season, but if he slides to eight he’ll be tough to pass on. He’s more outside linebacker than defensive end, but would give a big boost to the Lions pass rush.
Credit/Source: Bryan Woolston, AP, Bryan Woolston, AP

Caption: DE Rashan Gary, Michigan: Gary didn’t have a great 2018 season with just 3.5 sacks, and he appeared to coast at times with the draft on his mind. But he’s a big-time talent who could play end or tackle in Matt Patricia’s defense.
Credit/Source: Kirthmon F. Dozier, Detroit Free Press

Caption: DT Ed Oliver, Houston: Once considered in the conversation for the No. 1 overall pick, Oliver is a tremendous talent who had a quiet year. The Lions are stacked at DT with Damon Harrison, A’Shawn Robinson and Da’Shawn Hand, but Oliver is a blue-chip talent.

CB Greedy Williams, LSU: Williams is the No. 1 cornerback in this class and the Lions could use a cover man to play opposite Darius Slay. At 6 feet 3, he’s got tantalizing traits, though his aversion to run support seems counter to what Patricia wants.
Credit/Source: Gerald Herbert/Associated Press, Gerald Herbert/Associated Press

Caption: DE Clelin Ferrell, Clemson: Ferrell isn’t quite as talented as Allen, Gary or Oliver, but he should go in the top half of Round 1. He’s a dependable player, and at 6-5 and 265 pounds he’s got the size and length to play right end.

OLB Brian Burns, Florida State: There’s a lot of pass rushers on this list because, well, that's the Lions' biggest need. Burns will need to add weight to play right end, but he had an impressive 10-sack season.

5. Tampa Bay Buccaneers - OL Jonah Williams, Alabama: The Bucs could be in a sweet trade-down spot considering they pick in front of two quarterback-needy teams. Here, though, they take the best offensive lineman available.
LSU linebacker Devin White on the sideline during the game against Central Florida in the 2019 Fiesta Bowl.
Credit/Source: Mark J. Rebilas, USA TODAY Sports

Caption: DE Jaylon Ferguson, Louisiana Tech: If the Lions don’t take a defensive end up top, they'll need to grab one on Day 2. Ferguson played well at the Senior Bowl and holds the NCAA record for career sacks.

Caption: Michigan Wolverines assistant coach Tyrone Wheatley watches the action during spring practice March 26, 2016 at Ford Field in Detroit. (Photo: Kirthmon F. Dozier, DFP)
The 2019 Super Bowl is set for Sunday at Mercedez-Benz Stadium in Atlanta, Ga. Here's a look at players on the Los Angeles Rams and New England Patriots rosters with ties to the state of Michigan:
Credit/Source: John David Mercer, John David Mercer-USA TODAY Spor

Caption: DT Ndamukong Suh, Rams: The Lions made Suh the No. 2 overall pick in the 2010 NFL draft. Suh played five seasons in Detroit before signing with the Dolphins in 2015 and then the Rams in 2018. He helped form one of the most feared pass-rushing tandems in the NFL this season.
C Brian Allen, Rams: Allen made 38 starts over his four-year Michigan State career. A fourth-round draft pick, he has appeared in 12 games as a rookie this season.

KR/CB Blake Countess, Rams: Started 30 games at Michigan before transferring to Auburn. Selected in the sixth round of the 2016 draft by the Philadelphia Eagles. He was waived and then acquired by the Rams, and in November 2016 he was activated from their practice squad. Has averaged 24.6 yards on 17 punt returns this season but has made just nine tackles.

OT Jamil Demby, Rams: Lions acquired Demby off waivers from the Rams in September, then cut him and added him to their practice squad. The Rams re-signed Demby in December, but he has yet to appear in a game this season.
AST Jedd Fisch, Rams: Hired as a senior offensive assistant for the Rams in January 2018. Coached Michigan’s quarterbacks, wide receivers and was passing-game coordinator from 2015-16.
RB John Kelly, Rams: Kelly starred at Oak Park before a successful career at Tennessee. A sixth-round pick, he has rushed for 74 yards on 27 attempts as a rookie backup with the Rams.

HC Bill Belichick, Patriots: Belichick might go down as the greatest NFL coach of all-time. But long before he won five Super Bowls with the Patriots, he spent two seasons as a Lions assistant from 1976-1977.

QB Tom Brady, Patriots: Brady had a solid-but-not-spectacular career at Michigan, passing for nearly 4,800 yards and throwing 30 touchdowns against 17 interceptions from 1996-99. The Patriots selected him in the sixth round of the 2000 NFL draft in perhaps the biggest draft-day steal in history. Brady, 41, has won a NFL-record five Super Bowls, and he said recently he has no plans to retire anytime soon.
Credit/Source: Greg M. Cooper, USA TODAY Sports, Greg M. Cooper, USA TODAY Sports

Caption: Could Kentucky Wildcats standout Josh Allen be the Arizona Cardinals' No. 1 pick in the 2019 NFL draft? (Photo: Jasen Vinlove-USA TODAY Sports)
10. Denver Broncos - CB Greedy Williams, LSU: Denver’s once mighty secondary has slipped in recent years and Williams is the No. 1 cover man in the draft. (Photo: Matthew Emmons, USA TODAY Sports)

Jan 1, 2019; Glendale, AZ, USA; LSU Tigers linebacker Devin White (40) reacts in the fourth quarter against the UCF Knights in the 2019 Fiesta Bowl at State Farm Stadium. Mandatory Credit: Mark J. Rebilas-USA TODAY Sports (Photo: Mark J. Rebilas-USA TODAY Sports)
Ohio State's Parris Campbell had a monster game against Michigan, catching 6 passes for 192 yards and two touchdowns, one a 78-yarder. (Photo: Photo courtesy of George Fleiner)

OLB Josh Allen, Kentucky: Allen seems like a good bet to go in the top five after a 17-sack season, but if he slides to eight he’ll be tough to pass on. He’s more outside linebacker than defensive end, but would give a big boost to the Lions pass rush.
Credit/Source: Bryan Woolston, AP, Bryan Woolston, AP

Caption: DE Rashan Gary, Michigan: Gary didn’t have a great 2018 season with just 3.5 sacks, and he appeared to coast at times with the draft on his mind. But he’s a big-time talent who could play end or tackle in Matt Patricia’s defense.
Credit/Source: Kirthmon F. Dozier, Detroit Free Press

Caption: DT Ed Oliver, Houston: Once considered in the conversation for the No. 1 overall pick, Oliver is a tremendous talent who had a quiet year. The Lions are stacked at DT with Damon Harrison, A’Shawn Robinson and Da’Shawn Hand, but Oliver is a blue-chip talent.

CB Greedy Williams, LSU: Williams is the No. 1 cornerback in this class and the Lions could use a cover man to play opposite Darius Slay. At 6 feet 3, he’s got tantalizing traits, though his aversion to run support seems counter to what Patricia wants.
Credit/Source: Gerald Herbert/Associated Press, Gerald Herbert/Associated Press

Caption: DE Clelin Ferrell, Clemson: Ferrell isn’t quite as talented as Allen, Gary or Oliver, but he should go in the top half of Round 1. He’s a dependable player, and at 6-5 and 265 pounds he’s got the size and length to play right end.

OLB Brian Burns, Florida State: There’s a lot of pass rushers on this list because, well, that's the Lions' biggest need. Burns will need to add weight to play right end, but he had an impressive 10-sack season.

5. Tampa Bay Buccaneers - OL Jonah Williams, Alabama: The Bucs could be in a sweet trade-down spot considering they pick in front of two quarterback-needy teams. Here, though, they take the best offensive lineman available.
LSU linebacker Devin White on the sideline during the game against Central Florida in the 2019 Fiesta Bowl.
Credit/Source: Mark J. Rebilas, USA TODAY Sports

Caption: DE Jaylon Ferguson, Louisiana Tech: If the Lions don’t take a defensive end up top, they'll need to grab one on Day 2. Ferguson played well at the Senior Bowl and holds the NCAA record for career sacks.

TE T.J. Hockenson, Iowa: This is a deep draft at tight end, and the Lions might be in a sweet spot to land one at the top of Round 2. There’s no consensus No. 1 tight end right now between Hockenson, Alabama’s Irv Smith and Hockenson’s Iowa teammate, Noah Fant, and one or more of those will go in the first round.

Caption: Barry Sanders acknowledges the crowd after receiving a Pro Football Hall of Fame ring during a ceremony at halftime of a game between the Detroit Lions and the Chicago Bears on Oct. 18, 2015, in Detroit. (Photo: Jose Juarez, AP)
Los Angeles Rams nose tackle Ndamukong Suh during warmups before Super Bowl LIII against the New England Patriots in Atlanta, Feb. 3, 2019. (Photo: Robert Deutsch, USA TODAY Sports)
The 2019 Super Bowl is set for Sunday at Mercedez-Benz Stadium in Atlanta, Ga. Here's a look at players on the Los Angeles Rams and New England Patriots rosters with ties to the state of Michigan:
Credit/Source: John David Mercer, John David Mercer-USA TODAY Spor

Caption: DT Ndamukong Suh, Rams: The Lions made Suh the No. 2 overall pick in the 2010 NFL draft. Suh played five seasons in Detroit before signing with the Dolphins in 2015 and then the Rams in 2018. He helped form one of the most feared pass-rushing tandems in the NFL this season.
C Brian Allen, Rams: Allen made 38 starts over his four-year Michigan State career. A fourth-round draft pick, he has appeared in 12 games as a rookie this season.

KR/CB Blake Countess, Rams: Started 30 games at Michigan before transferring to Auburn. Selected in the sixth round of the 2016 draft by the Philadelphia Eagles. He was waived and then acquired by the Rams, and in November 2016 he was activated from their practice squad. Has averaged 24.6 yards on 17 punt returns this season but has made just nine tackles.

OT Jamil Demby, Rams: Lions acquired Demby off waivers from the Rams in September, then cut him and added him to their practice squad. The Rams re-signed Demby in December, but he has yet to appear in a game this season.
AST Jedd Fisch, Rams: Hired as a senior offensive assistant for the Rams in January 2018. Coached Michigan’s quarterbacks, wide receivers and was passing-game coordinator from 2015-16.
RB John Kelly, Rams: Kelly starred at Oak Park before a successful career at Tennessee. A sixth-round pick, he has rushed for 74 yards on 27 attempts as a rookie backup with the Rams.

HC Bill Belichick, Patriots: Belichick might go down as the greatest NFL coach of all-time. But long before he won five Super Bowls with the Patriots, he spent two seasons as a Lions assistant from 1976-1977.

Caption: With the 2019 NBA trade deadline Feb. 7, here are seven players that could be dealt who the Detroit Pistons have either reportedly been interested in or make sense to target in a trade. Of course, the Pistons could find a deal for someone not on this list as well. Let's get started (stats through Jan. 27) ...
Grizzlies guard Mike Conley. AGE: 31. SIZE: 6-1, 175. CONTRACT: $30.5 million this season, then 2 years, $67M. STATS: 20 PPG, 6.2 AST, 1.9 TOV, 35.6 3P%.
Grizzlies center Marc Gasol. AGE: 34. SIZE: 7-1, 255. CONTRACT: $24.1M this season, then 1 year, $25.6M player option. STATS: 15.4 PPG, 8.7 REB, 4.7 AST, 2.2 TOV, 1.2 BLK, 35.8 3P%.
Knicks guard Damyean Dotson. AGE: 24. SIZE: 6-6, 210. CONTRACT: $1.4M this season, $1.6 next season, non-guarenteed. STATS: 9.4 PPG, 3.5 REB, 37.7 3P%.
Heat guard Wayne Ellington. AGE: 31. SIZE: 6-5, 200. CONTRACT: $6.3M this season, unrestricted free agent in summer. STATS: 8.4 PPG, 1.9 REB, 37.1 3P%.
76ers guard Markelle Fultz. AGE: 20. SIZE: 6-4, 200. CONTRACT: $8.3M this season, then 2 years $22M on rookie deal. STATS: 8.2 PPG, 3.7 REB, 3.1 AST, 1.3 TOV, 41.9 FG%.
Hornets guard Kemba Walker. AGE: 28. SIZE: 6-1, 184. CONTRACT: $12M this season, unrestricted free agent in summer. STATS: 24.7 PPG, 5.6 AST, 4.3 REB, 2.6 TOV, 35.7 3P%.

Caption: The 2019 Super Bowl is set for Sunday at Mercedez-Benz Stadium in Atlanta, Ga. Here's a look at players on the Los Angeles Rams and New England Patriots rosters with ties to the state of Michigan:
Credit/Source: John David Mercer, John David Mercer-USA TODAY Spor

Caption: DT Ndamukong Suh, Rams: The Lions made Suh the No. 2 overall pick in the 2010 NFL draft. Suh played five seasons in Detroit before signing with the Dolphins in 2015 and then the Rams in 2018. He helped form one of the most feared pass-rushing tandems in the NFL this season.
C Brian Allen, Rams: Allen made 38 starts over his four-year Michigan State career. A fourth-round draft pick, he has appeared in 12 games as a rookie this season.

KR/CB Blake Countess, Rams: Started 30 games at Michigan before transferring to Auburn. Selected in the sixth round of the 2016 draft by the Philadelphia Eagles. He was waived and then acquired by the Rams, and in November 2016 he was activated from their practice squad. Has averaged 24.6 yards on 17 punt returns this season but has made just nine tackles.

OT Jamil Demby, Rams: Lions acquired Demby off waivers from the Rams in September, then cut him and added him to their practice squad. The Rams re-signed Demby in December, but he has yet to appear in a game this season.
AST Jedd Fisch, Rams: Hired as a senior offensive assistant for the Rams in January 2018. Coached Michigan’s quarterbacks, wide receivers and was passing-game coordinator from 2015-16.

The 2019 Super Bowl is set for Sunday at Mercedez-Benz Stadium in Atlanta, Ga. Here's a look at players on the Los Angeles Rams and New England Patriots rosters with ties to the state of Michigan:
Credit/Source: John David Mercer, John David Mercer-USA TODAY Spor

Caption: DT Ndamukong Suh, Rams: The Lions made Suh the No. 2 overall pick in the 2010 NFL draft. Suh played five seasons in Detroit before signing with the Dolphins in 2015 and then the Rams in 2018. He helped form one of the most feared pass-rushing tandems in the NFL this season.
C Brian Allen, Rams: Allen made 38 starts over his four-year Michigan State career. A fourth-round draft pick, he has appeared in 12 games as a rookie this season.

KR/CB Blake Countess, Rams: Started 30 games at Michigan before transferring to Auburn. Selected in the sixth round of the 2016 draft by the Philadelphia Eagles. He was waived and then acquired by the Rams, and in November 2016 he was activated from their practice squad. Has averaged 24.6 yards on 17 punt returns this season but has made just nine tackles.

OT Jamil Demby, Rams: Lions acquired Demby off waivers from the Rams in September, then cut him and added him to their practice squad. The Rams re-signed Demby in December, but he has yet to appear in a game this season.
AST Jedd Fisch, Rams: Hired as a senior offensive assistant for the Rams in January 2018. Coached Michigan’s quarterbacks, wide receivers and was passing-game coordinator from 2015-16.

With the 2019 NBA trade deadline Feb. 7, here are seven players that could be dealt who the Detroit Pistons have either reportedly been interested in or make sense to target in a trade. Of course, the Pistons could find a deal for someone not on this list as well. Let's get started (stats through Jan. 27) ...
Grizzlies guard Mike Conley. AGE: 31. SIZE: 6-1, 175. CONTRACT: $30.5 million this season, then 2 years, $67M. STATS: 20 PPG, 6.2 AST, 1.9 TOV, 35.6 3P%.
Grizzlies center Marc Gasol. AGE: 34. SIZE: 7-1, 255. CONTRACT: $24.1M this season, then 1 year, $25.6M player option. STATS: 15.4 PPG, 8.7 REB, 4.7 AST, 2.2 TOV, 1.2 BLK, 35.8 3P%.
Knicks guard Damyean Dotson. AGE: 24. SIZE: 6-6, 210. CONTRACT: $1.4M this season, $1.6 next season, non-guarenteed. STATS: 9.4 PPG, 3.5 REB, 37.7 3P%.
Heat guard Wayne Ellington. AGE: 31. SIZE: 6-5, 200. CONTRACT: $6.3M this season, unrestricted free agent in summer. STATS: 8.4 PPG, 1.9 REB, 37.1 3P%.
76ers guard Markelle Fultz. AGE: 20. SIZE: 6-4, 200. CONTRACT: $8.3M this season, then 2 years $22M on rookie deal. STATS: 8.2 PPG, 3.7 REB, 3.1 AST, 1.3 TOV, 41.9 FG%.
Hornets guard Kemba Walker. AGE: 28. SIZE: 6-1, 184. CONTRACT: $12M this season, unrestricted free agent in summer. STATS: 24.7 PPG, 5.6 AST, 4.3 REB, 2.6 TOV, 35.7 3P%.

With the 2019 NBA trade deadline Feb. 7, here are seven players that could be dealt who the Detroit Pistons have either reportedly been interested in or make sense to target in a trade. Of course, the Pistons could find a deal for someone not on this list as well. Let's get started (stats through Jan. 27) ...
Grizzlies guard Mike Conley. AGE: 31. SIZE: 6-1, 175. CONTRACT: $30.5 million this season, then 2 years, $67M. STATS: 20 PPG, 6.2 AST, 1.9 TOV, 35.6 3P%.
Grizzlies center Marc Gasol. AGE: 34. SIZE: 7-1, 255. CONTRACT: $24.1M this season, then 1 year, $25.6M player option. STATS: 15.4 PPG, 8.7 REB, 4.7 AST, 2.2 TOV, 1.2 BLK, 35.8 3P%.
Knicks guard Damyean Dotson. AGE: 24. SIZE: 6-6, 210. CONTRACT: $1.4M this season, $1.6 next season, non-guarenteed. STATS: 9.4 PPG, 3.5 REB, 37.7 3P%.
Heat guard Wayne Ellington. AGE: 31. SIZE: 6-5, 200. CONTRACT: $6.3M this season, unrestricted free agent in summer. STATS: 8.4 PPG, 1.9 REB, 37.1 3P%.
76ers guard Markelle Fultz. AGE: 20. SIZE: 6-4, 200. CONTRACT: $8.3M this season, then 2 years $22M on rookie deal. STATS: 8.2 PPG, 3.7 REB, 3.1 AST, 1.3 TOV, 41.9 FG%.
Hornets guard Kemba Walker. AGE: 28. SIZE: 6-1, 184. CONTRACT: $12M this season, unrestricted free agent in summer. STATS: 24.7 PPG, 5.6 AST, 4.3 REB, 2.6 TOV, 35.7 3P%.
Wizards guard Bradley Beal. AGE: 25. SIZE: 6-5, 207. CONTRACT: $25.4M this season, then 2 years, $55.8M. STATS: 24.6 PPG, 5 AST, 5.1 REB, 2.8 TOV, 35.5 3P%.
Pistons center Andre Drummond dunks next to Bucks forward Giannis Antetokounmpo during the second half of the Pistons' 115-105 loss on Tuesday, Jan. 29, 2019, at Little Caesars Arena.

With the 2019 NBA trade deadline Feb. 7, here are seven players that could be dealt who the Detroit Pistons have either reportedly been interested in or make sense to target in a trade. Of course, the Pistons could find a deal for someone not on this list as well. Let's get started (stats through Jan. 27) ...
Grizzlies guard Mike Conley. AGE: 31. SIZE: 6-1, 175. CONTRACT: $30.5 million this season, then 2 years, $67M. STATS: 20 PPG, 6.2 AST, 1.9 TOV, 35.6 3P%.
Grizzlies center Marc Gasol. AGE: 34. SIZE: 7-1, 255. CONTRACT: $24.1M this season, then 1 year, $25.6M player option. STATS: 15.4 PPG, 8.7 REB, 4.7 AST, 2.2 TOV, 1.2 BLK, 35.8 3P%.
Knicks guard Damyean Dotson. AGE: 24. SIZE: 6-6, 210. CONTRACT: $1.4M this season, $1.6 next season, non-guarenteed. STATS: 9.4 PPG, 3.5 REB, 37.7 3P%.
Heat guard Wayne Ellington. AGE: 31. SIZE: 6-5, 200. CONTRACT: $6.3M this season, unrestricted free agent in summer. STATS: 8.4 PPG, 1.9 REB, 37.1 3P%.
76ers guard Markelle Fultz. AGE: 20. SIZE: 6-4, 200. CONTRACT: $8.3M this season, then 2 years $22M on rookie deal. STATS: 8.2 PPG, 3.7 REB, 3.1 AST, 1.3 TOV, 41.9 FG%.
Hornets guard Kemba Walker. AGE: 28. SIZE: 6-1, 184. CONTRACT: $12M this season, unrestricted free agent in summer. STATS: 24.7 PPG, 5.6 AST, 4.3 REB, 2.6 TOV, 35.7 3P%.
Wizards guard Bradley Beal. AGE: 25. SIZE: 6-5, 207. CONTRACT: $25.4M this season, then 2 years, $55.8M. STATS: 24.6 PPG, 5 AST, 5.1 REB, 2.8 TOV, 35.5 3P%.
